test: Miriam wanted to work at Mckinsey. Worked previously at teach for america where she worked on analytical skills and teamwork. She is founder of the Booth educational club and used power of persuasion to get funding.

The candidate worked at Citigroup in their leveraged finance team, working mainly on LBOs.  He was offered the opportunity to remain with the firm as an associate, but chose to return to India to work for a home furnishings company.   That company was struggling and he was attempting to turn it around as much as possible within 2 years.  He know wants to work in a general management role at MetLife.

worked as an analyst at citigroup in levfin, said he was promoted twice. decided to move to india to help turn around a struggling business. was the most difficult decision of his life but believed taking that opportunity would be a better learning experience than continuing on as an associate in his current function.

The candidate was applying for a job with McKinsey, specifically. However might be looking for consulting positions with a premium firm. He believes that the most important characteristics for a consultant work communications, analytics, teamwork, entrepreneurship. He was a Teacher for teach for America where he felt he demonstrated analytics through his metric driven education of children; he demonstrated entrepreneurship by starting new club on campus, had demonstrated communication skills, which were seen in presentations that he made, one of which was in San Antonio.

Applied for a job at McKinsey, was a teacher in Brooklyn, started industry club at Booth- got admin approval & budget money for club, convinced San Antonio mayor to give budget for sustainable project in a local school, worked at a mgmt consulting firm over the summer & worked in teams

Previously worked at Citigroup for 3 years - then had to go back to India to help a struggling business. He was given 2 years to help turn the struggling business around and it was overall a great learning experience for him. He now wants a job at Metlife

The candidat wants to work at Spotify because he is passionate about the application but he didn't seem confident or very well spoken. He did mention what he's done in the past and what he can bring to the table but there wasn't enough conviction in his voice as though he was doubting himself.

Worked at a small consulting firm. In his/her past job, focused a lot on understanding consumer behavior. Wants to use what they learned at the consulting firm and apply it to Spotify. Wants to be in a consumer facing role. Had bad grammar and used unprofessional language (i.e. really really). Also, used contradicting language (i.e. kind of really important). Seemed passionate about the role but didnt effectively show they they would be competent in the role.

The candidate was interested in a general management position at Metlife.  He spent 3 years prior to B-School in the financial services industry where he learned a great deal -- analytical skills, building relationships, etc.  He was promoted twice during his time there and then decided to return to India to help a failing furniture company turn their business around.  He feels that his past experience is a good match for the role at Metlife.

- Applying for a job at Metlife / - Started off in leverage finance at Citibank / - at the 3 year mark, they could have stayed but decided to try something different / - Went back to India to take over a business and turn it around / - Wanted to gain more

Wanted to work at Spotify, apply skills from previous job to Tech industry, had done data analysis including studying attrition rates at previous company, Spotify is really the only app he is passionate about, really likes how Spotify is impacting music industry, wants to be in consumer-facing role

Currently at Booth  / Worked at CitiGroup raising debt  / Went back to India to work for a failing business / Wasn't sure this was a good idea because of the stable job with CitiGroup, but wanted to get the entrepreneurial experience

Has a background in customer attrition and working with large amounts of data.  Says he/she has a 'sort of' very positive attitude.  Said he/she would bring a lot of experience to the roll.

The student is interested in a job at Metlife. He/She previously worked at CitiGroup in their leverage finance team in NYC. She wanted to work at McK so she gave background information including her analytic abilities, her previous work in consulting , her ability to drive change by instituting a new club and also communication skills.

His prior work experience- however to be honest what I heard took away from his credentials- this candidate used the word um so many times throughout the conversation- without seeing him - and only listening to his voice- use of the word "um" was so overpowering it took away- also his voice tone- it was very monotone- not showing much excitement about what he was describing- also took away from remembering what he actually said-
Promoted twice at a consulting firm, but left to return to India to turn around a struggling business. Looking to learn.

The student worked at Citi for 3 years prior to ChicagoBooth. During that time the candidate received 2 promotions. Then the candidate decided to move to India to help turn a struggling furniture business around. The candidate did this because they wanted to have more of an impact and thought it would be a great learning experience. Based on that experience, that is why the candidate thinks they're a good fit for MetLife.

Spotify- product manager role / likes the industry and was up to date on company  / genuine passion for music / worked in a legit start-up / previously used valuable tools / logically order of pitch / touched on hard and soft skills

Prior work experience includes a small consulting shop founded by Levitt and a co-founder (surname starts with a "K") that attempts to take academic tools and apply them in real world situations.  The candidate is an interested in a position in tech and prior work experience and interest in / liking of Spotify are reasons why this candidate may be a good fit.

Gave examples of when he displayed those competencies through being a teacher, a student group organizer/leader, and when he worked on a consulting project. He did not give any specific metrics or data points of accomplishments, just used a lot of superlatives (really, very, extremely....).

He's very excited about the opportunity at Spotify and what the company is doing in the music industry. He worked in some sort of firm during the summer that will give him the experience needed to apply to the position at Spotify specifically around data analytics.
The student wanted to work at Spotify and had a good background for the job, but his reasonings for wanting Spotify specifically seemed slightly vague.

He's entrepeneurial, likes challenges, and he's hoping to get a position with MetLife.;
